                            Link = "https://www.ruv.is/frett/2022/01/18/scientists-salute-six-special-sheep",
                            Origin = "Ruv",
                            Summary = "An important discovery has been made on Þernunes farm in Reyðarfjörður: six sheep that bear a gene recognised by the European Union as a protection against scrapie. It is the first time the genotype has been discovered in sheep in Iceland, despite years of searching. The discovery could be pivotal in the fight against scrapie, if research in other European countries can be replicated. The genome, called ARR, has never been found in Iceland before; though another rare one called T137 was recently discovered, and has been providing good results in anti-scrapie research in Italy—though is not yet recognised on the European level.\n\nFor just over two decades, it has been known that ARR protects sheep from scrapie, which is an incurable and infectious brain disease, the discovery of which requires whole flocks to be culled. In the EU, farms are no longer required to cull exposed sheep with the ARR genome, because it is believed to be nearly impossible for them to catch or transmit the disease.&nbsp;\n\nIcelandic scientists re-started their search for the gene last spring, taking samples from Icelandic sheep in both Iceland and Greenland. Of 4,200 samples, only two, from one farm, came back positive. Re-testing at the farm confirmed the result and added four more sheep to the valuable gene pool: five ewes and one ram lamb.&nbsp;\n\nThe animals are hornless and trace their roots to hornless sheep in the Reykhólar and Strandir areas of the Westfjords.&nbsp;\n\nA statement from the researchers says there is now hope that the ARR genome will be found in other regions as well. The encouraging discovery means 15,000 more sheep will be tested this winter with the challenging aim both of spreading the ARR genome widely in the national flock, and also preserving genetic diversity.&nbsp;\n\nClick to follow RÚV English on Facebook. \n ",
